he Volga and Mississippi Rivers persist in the collective memory and continue to offer solace, recreation, and sustenance. Through their histories we derive a more nuanced view of human interaction with the environment, which adds another lens to our understanding of the past.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Nov 2022) 0aCollective memoryzRussiaxHistory. 0aCollective memoryzUnited StatesxHistory. 0aHuman ecologyzRussiaxHistory. 0aHuman ecologyzUnited StatesxHistory. 0aNationalismzRussiaxHistory. 0aNationalismzUnited StatesxHistory. 0aRiversxSocial aspectszRussia. 0aRiversxSocial aspectszUnited States. 7aHISTORY / Historical Geography.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBerghahn Books Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311099823840uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978178238432840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781782384328423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781782384328/original  a978-3-11-099823-8  Berghahn Books Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK